In addition, durable dual-side transparent windows allow for quick determination of approximate number of rounds remaining in the magazine. Utilizing a high visibility indicator coil on the spring and numerical markers on the magazine body, the MagLevel™ system provides positive verification without affecting the durability or reliability of the magazine. The GEN M2 MOE is identical in form and function to the older model PMAG except that the optional Impact/Dust Cover is now sold separately. Made in U.S.A.

The Heckler & Koch P2000 is a German semi-automatic pistol introduced late in 2001 and intended primarily for law enforcement, paramilitary, and commercial markets. It is based on the USP Compact pistol. The P2000 was designed specifically with improved ergonomic characteristics; it has features that reduce handling related stresses, while at the same time increasing user handling and comfort.

The P2000 is a short recoil-operated locked breech pistol with a modified Browning-type linkless cam action with a vertically tilting barrel also employed in the USP series of self-loading pistols, as well as most modern linkless semi autos.

The cold hammer-forged barrel has a polygonal profile while the slide is made from a solid bar of nitro-carburized steel. Following recent trends in modern pistol design, the P2000 makes extensive use of impact-resistant polymers to reduce weight and production costs.

As with other recent Heckler & Koch pistol designs, the P2000 is modular to suit individual needs. For instance, the grip is modular with exchangeable backstraps, allowing the user to customize the pistol's grip size and feel. There is a universal accessory rail built into the dust cover in front of the trigger guard that allows for the use of tactical lights, laser pointers and other accessories. This is in contrast with the USP series which uses a proprietary H&K mounting rail that limits the types of accessories that could be used with the pistol.

The P2000 is a hammer-fired pistol with an exposed spurred hammer; a bobbed hammer is optional. It has an ambidextrous slide lock and a fully ambidextrous magazine release installed in the trigger guard.

title: For Sale:  3 Original Civil War Era Muskets
postcontent:
I have the following Civil War era muskets for sale:

Austrian M1854 "Lorenz" Rifle Musket with original bayonet and an original US made scabbard. Musket is in good condition with a nice stock with crisp edges. Some bumps and bruises due to long and hard use, but much nicer than many. 
The metal has deep chocolate brown patina, but is arsenal bright where covered by barrel bands. Some light pinpricking around the breech and bolster area. The lock is unmarked and there is no visible makers stamp on the barrel. The bore is .57 caliber and has very strong rifling. $1,150

Pedimontese M1844/60 .69 caliber rifle musket with original bayonet. Very nice condition musket made by F&T (Falisse and Trapmann) of Liege, Belgium in 1861 as evident by the lock stampings. Barrel has several Belgian proofmarks. 
The stock is in very good shape with minimal wear. The bayonet is in good condition, with some old pitting and is developing a nice mottled patina. It is a very tight fit for the gun and is missing the locking ring. $950

Percussion converted Smith Cogswell M1808 .69 caliber musket. A very cool old percussion altered M1808 musket. This gun was originally built as a flintlock for the State of New York, as evident by the ownership marks on the barrel, and was converted to percussion using the French, or drum method. Where this one differs is that the original flint cock was retained and a crude, abet functional striker was brazed onto the face of the cock to allow it to operate correctly.
The barrel appears to have been cleaned at some point. The stock has a break through the wrist that was repaired. The repair is visible, but very solid. I think the the mainspring is broken, but have not removed the lock to see. There is tension enough for the hammer to operate, but there may not be enough force to break a percussion cap.
The stock has an interesting modification removing the middle barrel band and thinning the stock to remove the band step. The front sight/barrel band has been filed flat across the top and the bayonet lug has been modified into a new front sight. $800 

Photos may be viewed here: https://www.dropbox.com/sh/dg0cmk8i7yplawj/AAA9bT3Y4oUxztHgW-5X6Drda?dl=0
